		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>NES sound mod</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hello! I have a Toaster NES with a generic famicom adapter and a copy of akumajou densetsu and I would like to mod my NES to play the additional music but I have not been able to find a clear guide anywhere. Does anyone have experience with this mod?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Super-Hampster</b> [ Wed Jul 13, 2011 12:54 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Sure. You need a 100k ohm resistor and a 4.7uF Capacitor. Use them to connect the audio out pin of your Famicom cart to pin 3 on the expansion port. 
<br />
<br />famicom cart pin 46 --&gt; 100k ohm resistor --&gt; 4.7uF Capacitor --&gt; pin 3 of NES expansion port. 
<br />
<br />I used test probe wire and the copper wire out of a cat5 cable. Here are some pics. 
<br />
<br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/adaptermod3.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/adaptermod2.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/adaptermod.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/audiomod1.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
<br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/capandresistor.jpg" alt="Image" />
<br />
